HT|E|CS|1|CP|4|AT|^-{    HOW TO DECIDE WHETHER TO DUCK    }
^-|CS||CP||HT|f|AT|^B@2^Y@3Consider the following diagrams of heart distribution:
|ht|H|at|^D@H A K 8 7 6 5 ^L@H A K 8 7 6 5 |HT|I|FP|2|AT|^B1 ^J2|
HT|J|fp||AT|^D@h 4 3      ^L@H 4 3 2 |
PG| ***** 74 ***** |


AT|
 
The first shows a partnership holding of eight cards headed by Ace-King; the second, a partnership holding of nine cards headed by Ace-King. Naturally, the second combination is considerably better than the first. The first is a simple illustration of the necessity to duck a round of hearts in order to preserve an entry: you merely concede the first round of the suit to your Opponents, hoping that the distribution of the five adverse hearts is 3-2 (if they are otherwise distributed, there is nothing you can do about it—to duck is still your best play).|
PG| ***** 75 ***** |


AT|

The second situation is somewhat different. With only four hearts outstanding against you, you can lead the Ace and King and drop all four if they are divided 2-2. But it is altogether possible—and even likely—that the four adverse hearts are distributed 3-1. What, then, should you do? The answer is that you cannot tell without seeing the rest of the outstanding cards. If the Dummy contains a re-entry outside the heart suit, the proper play is to lead the Ace and King pronto, and, if these two leads fail to capture all the adverse hearts, you should lead another heart right away. |
PG| ***** 76 ***** |


AT|

But if the Dummy does not contain a re-entry, you cannot afford to take the chance of finding the adverse hearts divided 2-2, particularly if you hold a certain degree of control over the other three suits. In other words, if you can see your way clear to making your contract even though you concede 1 heart trick to the Opponents, |cp|8|at|you should lose that trick faster than you can say Jack Robinson|cp||at|—so that you can be sure of 5 heart tricks eventually, and not hope for 6 heart tricks and perhaps take only 2! You do this, of course, by leading a low heart from your hand, and ducking in the Dummy no matter what West plays.|
PG| ***** 77 ***** |


NT||
HT|E|CS|1|CP|4|AT|^-{    HOW TO DECIDE WHETHER TO DUCK - Continued    }
^-|CS||CP||HT|f|AT|^B@2^Y@3If, in the end, it turns out that your ducking play in the second instance has actually lost you a trick on this particular deal, the number of points you have sacrificed is not great enough to offset the safety value of the ducking play. Again, if the situation is so desperate that you cannot afford to give up 1 heart trick at once, thereby losing the lead, you cannot afford, naturally, to play safe. |FP|2|cp|8|at|The man who is dying of starvation cannot afford to pay for life insurance!|FP||cp||at| But whenever you are certain that the loss of a few tricks at once, to insure a measure of safety, will not in any event cost you your contract, you must "|FP|2|cp|8|at|play safe|cp||AT|."|
